review_blob: Pours a dark amber color and a tan head. Aroma is caramel, slightly floral, with a touch of grapefruit. Initial taste of caramel malt sweetness but finishes with a nice dose of hoppy bitterness.
Pours a hazy orange color with a big offwhite head. Aroma of rye, caramel, and hop. Taste is a nice combination of rye and bitter hops. A bit creamy at the palate.
beer_name: Bear Republic Hop Rod Rye Ale

review_blob: Pours a very dark brown color with a tiny creamy head and lacings. Aroma of roasted barely, coffee and chocolate. Taste of Caramel, milk chocolate and dough, caramel. Medium bodied.
beer_name: Left Hand Wake Up Dead Imperial Stout

review_blob: Pours black color with a small tan head. Aromas are roasted malts and coffee, with some dark chocolate hints. Mouth-feel is medium bodied and coats the palate well. Tastes are similar to aromas.
beer_name: Bear Republic Big Bear Black Stout

review_blob: Dark brown with a consistent though shallow light brown head. Coffee and chocolate come through fairly well. Taste is roasted through out. Coffee finish,with maybe a hint of chocolate.
Clear gold, average head and retention. Smell of roasted malts and hops carried a mild pleasing aroma. The taste was of a bitter and tart with a hoppy and spice flavors.
Medium Amber color. Nose smelled of grass and malt. Taste was of sweet roasted malt. It also had a nice spicy hop bite. Crisp and smooth.
Amber color with a lot of carbonation and a creamy head. Malty aroma and taste, with a hop tingle in the finish. Perfectly balanced, with a smooth medium body. Very drinkable.
Dark brown with a thick head. Smell is thick with syrupy malt and some caramel notes. Taste is caramel malt, then a fairly strong dose of hop bitterness.

Pours a nice black with a thick foamy head that quickly disappears. The smell was a little sweet with a roasted malt aroma. Taste comes in with a round caramel and toasty flavor with a little coffee, and ends on a sweet, but crisp finish.

Dark but clear amber colored body with a modest head that quickly dissipates and leaves little lacing.  Light aroma of corn and pale malt. Also had a faint smell of fresh grain. Taste is light caramel malt with a pale malt note and light hop bitterness and a light corn note.

Solid black with a fizzy tan head that fades down after a few minutes, spotty lacing. Got the scent of nutty malt, dark chocolate with a hint of mild coffee.  Flavors of roasted malt upfront followed by more subtle hints of dark chocolate coffee, and oats and is rounded out with a hint of hops. Has a crisp and smooth, medium to full bodied mouthfeel.

Orange amber color with finger head and lots of lacing all around. Sweet candy and fresh hop aroma. Flavor is fruity and piney hops. The hops flavor is very fresh. There is just enough malt to back up the hops. Very bitter finish. Medium mouthfeel.

Deep dark ruby brown witha fluffy rocky light coffee colored head. The aroma is milky, slightly roasty, with a nice oakiness throughout. Taste some roasted flavors hints of chocolate then strong cherry flavors.
Very dark oak brown. The smell is sweet dark chocolate and roasted malt. Taste is burnt malt bitterness giving way to sweet dark fruit.  Hops are strong and citrusy coming in at the end. Full bodied.

Dark amber/copper color. Lightly-hopped nose with a balancing malt presence. Slightly citrusy when cold with touches of lemon. Taste was piney with a little floral aspect on the side, then lots of toasty malt flavor.
Pale gold color with a 2+ finger white head. Smell is sweet and grainy with a very tiny hint of floral hops. Taste is very light, and unoffensive. Not very complex, but good drinkability.
beer_name: Flying Dog Tire Bite Golden Ale

review_blob: Amber/copper orange. Good size creamy head. Smells very herbal, with hops coming on strong. Taste is solid and balanced, a firm dose of hops with enough malt backbone to keep up. Nicely balanced.

Clear golden straw hue with a half-inch stark white head. Nice carbonation. Nose of sharp floral, grassy hops and crisp, clean lager yeast. Palate begins with more of the same, then develops a sharper hoppiness. Medium bodied.
pale straw, gold; off white head that laces lightly. Smell is a mix of grains and grassy, citrusy hops.Tasted of malt, a grassy component, light fruit, and a slight hoppy tinge. Well carbonated.

Copper color with a dense head of foam. Medium levels of carbonation, and mild lacing in the glass .Aromas that are sweet and a small amount of grapefruity hops. Smooth, small hop presenceand a dry end. It does have a small dry aftertaste.

Dark brown with a nice tan head.The aroma is malty and smoky with earthy hints of coffee and chocolate. Well balanced between lightly burnt/roasty and smokey sweet malt and good bittering hop flavor. Medium bodied.
Clear orange color. Airy off-white head dissipates quickly. Has a good semi-spicy aroma. Nice flavor of spicy hops with some malt. Light-bodied and smooth. Its pretty crisp and refreshing.

Hazy amber in color with a creamy off-white head and lacing. notable aromas of citrus and resiny pine. taste was a moderate sweetness with a long, bitter finish. medium to full-bodied.  Good drinkability.

Poured a clear golden color with a small lingering white head. The smell is very light, slightly sweet with some very light hops. Flavor is light and bready with a slight citrus touch. Finishes very clean, with only a touch of hops.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Pours nearly black with a massive foamy head. Malty with aromas of toffee, molasses, and a bit of alcohol. Malty flavors of burnt oak and coffee followed by quite a bit of hop bitterness. Lots of alcoholic heat, but with good drinkability.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Pink with an equally pink head. Smell is very faint and undetectable. There is a little sweetness in the nose with a slight vegetable smell.Tastes sweet upfront  and a weird aftertaste.

black with a large mocha frothy mostly lasting head with good lacing. Smelt of strong coffee cream and sugar, with light burnt grain notes.  Taste was upfront strong bitter coffee with moderate cream and sugar, and dark molasses sweetness followed by more strong bitter coffee and moderate sweet creaminess and sugar with bitter roasted grain on a long coffee finish. Palate was medium to full bodied.

Orange body with a thin white head that slowly fades away into a faint ring. Earthy, grapefruit/piney hops dominate the aroma. Some caramel/citrusy sweetness. Caramel malts and spicy hop flavor both well balanced. Very nice IPA.

Pours a very deep brown/black with a nice head. Nose of roasted malt, espresso and subtle hints of chocoltae and caramel. Rich coffee flavor with notes of caramel.  Good medium body brew with a very good level of carbonation and is smooth. Aftertaste of roasted malts.
Pours pale yellow with a lot of carbonation and a big head that settles quickly. Not much aroma and the taste is also very light. Not a bad light beer is that is what you are looking for.
Dark brown, with hints of red, tan head that lingers and excellent lacing. Aroma of malt, and dark fruit. Taste is predominantly dark fruit with hints of chocolate. Good drinkability.

Copper color with a rather large white head that leaves good lacing throughout.  A biscuity smell is the most present with some hop smells as well.  The hops hit upfront, but are not strong and it is followed by a taste that is mostly bread-like. There is a hint of sweetness in the finish as well.
beer_name: Black Sheep Monty Pythons Holy Grail (Bottle)

review_blob: Golden amber color-good carbonation level-has a decent head. Somewhat hoppy aroma.Bitterness is right upfront with minimal malt. A bit unbalanced in my opinion. Average mouthfeel.
Golden hue with faint aromas of malt and honey. The beer was lite on the palate and good drinkability.
If you dropped a drop of beer in pint glass of water then I think you would get Coors light.
Very very pale yellow. Not much taste, not much aroma, not much body. Not much of anything.

Orangish amber color with a thin white head with good retention that sticks all over the sides of the glass. The aroma is malt, a floral sweetness, bubblegum, vanilla and alcohol. Taste is creamy with a nice maltiness in the beginning that is followed with a flowery and fruitiness with the hops rounding out the finish and some warming from the alcohol.

Black with a off white head.aroma bitter sweet choc. black licorice,malts, caramel, molasses, light smoke, coffee, hops. flavor, black licorice,bitter sweet chocolate caramel, molasses, coffee,hops with malts and cherries thrown in.

Pale orange color with perfect clarity. Head is smooth and creamy.  Smells of caramel, English toffee, rum, and some orange. Surprisingly not overwhelmingly boozy. Big malt flavors-caramel, toffee, and toast. Good drinkability.
Pale yellow with a tall white head that resolved quickly. no lacing to speak of. malty aroma and taste. Not bad and drinkable, but nothing special.

Amber brown color into my way overchilled mug. I had to wait several minutes for the beer to warm up before my first taste. The smell is malty and a little nutty also. Taste is quite good for a mega brewery, with notes of chocolate, caramel and malty sweetness.

Pitch-black porter with a small foamy dark head with average retention. Aroma of chocolate is well mix with some roasted malt. Taste is a mixture between sweet malt with slight roasted bitter touch and some smooth chocolate undertones. Creamy texture.

Cloudy yellow color with a pure white head, and has a spicy aroma including coriander, clove, orange peel and a hint of banana. The spices are full in the flavor, and combine with a bit of yeastiness and muffled bitterness.

Dark amber with a bit of a lacy white head that trails down the glass. Malty nose, some faint chocolate but not much else. Tad bit of grassy hop leaves in the background. Sweet and malty, brown sugary at the front but fairly watery toward the end.
Golden yellow pour, high carbonation and grainy nose and flavor. Bottom line..its an okay beer for the price if you drink it ice cold.

Pale yellow-gold color with a thin and short-lasting white head. Specks of lacing on the glass. Mild aroma of hops and grainy malt. Light-bodied with an unappealing flavor profile of grain, corn and weak hops.
Oh good old Old Milwaukee. I have good memories with you in college. The taste though is something entirely different.
Very light yellow with not much aroma to speak of. Taste is corn and hoppy bitterness. Not bad if you drink cold and fast.
Honestly, I cant tell you the difference between all the Macro light beers. They are all equally bad.
